WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.330 --> 00:00:01.880
CHRISTINE: Christine
[INAUDIBLE].

00:00:01.880 --> 00:00:04.170
I'm a member of our
legal team.

00:00:04.170 --> 00:00:07.940
And I somehow got tricked into
doing this event because I was

00:00:07.940 --> 00:00:10.060
so excited to meet Cheryl.

00:00:10.060 --> 00:00:12.620
For those of you who don't know,
Cheryl Strayed is a New

00:00:12.620 --> 00:00:14.580
York Times best-selling
author.

00:00:14.580 --> 00:00:17.410
She had two books come out in
the last year, "Wild," which

00:00:17.410 --> 00:00:23.580
was her memoir of her
three-month solo trip up the

00:00:23.580 --> 00:00:26.910
Pacific Crest Trail of hiking
more than 1,000 miles.

00:00:26.910 --> 00:00:29.190
She also had a book come out
called "Tiny Beautiful

00:00:29.190 --> 00:00:32.759
Things," which is a compendium,
I don't know, a

00:00:32.759 --> 00:00:37.630
collection of her columns that
she wrote as Dear Sugar.

00:00:37.630 --> 00:00:40.800
And "Dear Sugar" was an advice
column on the Rumpus.

00:00:40.800 --> 00:00:41.400
Still is.

00:00:41.400 --> 00:00:42.700
CHERYL STRAYED: Yes.

00:00:42.700 --> 00:00:45.890
CHRISTINE: But, sort of advice
column that transcended the

00:00:45.890 --> 00:00:48.390
bounds of advice columns.

00:00:48.390 --> 00:00:50.810
She's also the author of a
critically acclaimed novel

00:00:50.810 --> 00:00:55.940
called "Torch." And she has an
MFA from Syracuse University

00:00:55.940 --> 00:01:02.205
and a PA from the University
of Minnesota.

00:01:02.205 --> 00:01:04.879
And she lives in Portland
with two kids.

00:01:04.879 --> 00:01:05.620
CHERYL STRAYED: And
my husband.

00:01:05.620 --> 00:01:06.520
CHRISTINE: And her husband.

00:01:06.520 --> 00:01:08.055
CHERYL STRAYED: And
our three cats.

00:01:08.055 --> 00:01:08.840
CHRISTINE: Three cats?

00:01:08.840 --> 00:01:09.635
CHERYL STRAYED: Three, yeah.

00:01:09.635 --> 00:01:10.530
CHRISTINE: That's
a lot of cats.

00:01:10.530 --> 00:01:12.460
CHERYL STRAYED: That's
a lot of cats.

00:01:12.460 --> 00:01:13.170
CHRISTINE: So welcome.

00:01:13.170 --> 00:01:14.390
We're so excited to have you.

00:01:14.390 --> 00:01:14.650
CHERYL STRAYED: Thank you.

00:01:14.650 --> 00:01:15.390
It's great to be here.

00:01:15.390 --> 00:01:17.010
And thank you all for coming.

00:01:17.010 --> 00:01:19.040
Oh, thanks.

00:01:19.040 --> 00:01:21.260
CHRISTINE: So, we
had lunch today.

00:01:21.260 --> 00:01:23.250
And Cheryl has seen all
of the Google perks.

00:01:23.250 --> 00:01:26.020
So I think the next step, Laslo,
is maybe that we need

00:01:26.020 --> 00:01:27.563
an artist in residence.

00:01:27.563 --> 00:01:28.310
CHERYL STRAYED: Yeah.

00:01:28.310 --> 00:01:29.480
We're thinking.

00:01:29.480 --> 00:01:31.440
I could split my time,
artist in residence

00:01:31.440 --> 00:01:33.370
and hiker in residence.

00:01:33.370 --> 00:01:34.310
CHRISTINE: We have plenty
of trails around here.

00:01:34.310 --> 00:01:34.706
CHERYL STRAYED: That's right.

00:01:34.706 --> 00:01:35.500
That's right.

00:01:35.500 --> 00:01:37.720
Somebody needs to take you
guys on those trails.

00:01:37.720 --> 00:01:41.540
CHRISTINE: So, the last year of
your life, I think, must be

00:01:41.540 --> 00:01:43.040
something that you couldn't
have anticipated.

00:01:43.040 --> 00:01:46.850
Did you anticipate that both
"Tiny Beautiful Things" and

00:01:46.850 --> 00:01:49.340
"Wild" would have exploded
like this when you were

00:01:49.340 --> 00:01:51.410
writing them and publishing
them?

00:01:51.410 --> 00:01:52.850
CHERYL STRAYED: No.

00:01:52.850 --> 00:01:56.830
And yet, there's a longer
answer to that question.

00:01:56.830 --> 00:02:03.050
It has to do with essentially
what I had to do along the way

00:02:03.050 --> 00:02:04.550
as I became a writer.

00:02:04.550 --> 00:02:08.650
When I was in my early 20s and
I had all of these ambitions

00:02:08.650 --> 00:02:11.580
to be a writer and was really
studying the writer's craft

00:02:11.580 --> 00:02:17.270
and writing my first stories,
I had these grandiose ideas

00:02:17.270 --> 00:02:19.200
about what it meant to be a
writer that I think a lot of

00:02:19.200 --> 00:02:22.820
times people early in their
careers as writers they think,

00:02:22.820 --> 00:02:23.910
OK, I'm gonna write this book.

00:02:23.910 --> 00:02:26.030
I am gonna be on the best seller
list, or I'll be a

00:02:26.030 --> 00:02:27.510
famous author.

00:02:27.510 --> 00:02:32.350
And then the more you work,
the more you come to

00:02:32.350 --> 00:02:35.680
understand that you really
cannot measure

00:02:35.680 --> 00:02:37.400
success in that way.

00:02:37.400 --> 00:02:39.990
Your book being on the best
seller list is not an accurate

00:02:39.990 --> 00:02:44.220
gauge of success when you're
a literary artist.

00:02:44.220 --> 00:02:48.510
And I say that with great
confidence because I know so

00:02:48.510 --> 00:02:52.690
many fantastic writers who are
writing beautiful work worthy

00:02:52.690 --> 00:02:54.480
of our attention that
they don't ever

00:02:54.480 --> 00:02:56.000
really get our attention.

00:02:56.000 --> 00:03:00.290
And so, I had to really come
to grips with that pretty

00:03:00.290 --> 00:03:03.590
early on and say the way I was
going to measure success as a

00:03:03.590 --> 00:03:07.070
writer was to always do the best
work I could, to put my

00:03:07.070 --> 00:03:12.200
full self into it, to do my
work, to study the craft, and

00:03:12.200 --> 00:03:15.010
to write fearlessly with great
vulnerability, and

00:03:15.010 --> 00:03:17.990
then come what may.

00:03:17.990 --> 00:03:21.470
What's so fascinating to me is
"Wild" would be the exact same

00:03:21.470 --> 00:03:25.350
book whether two people had read
it or two million people

00:03:25.350 --> 00:03:26.660
had read it.

00:03:26.660 --> 00:03:27.660
That book what exist.

00:03:27.660 --> 00:03:30.830
I would not have done anything
differently.

00:03:30.830 --> 00:03:33.080
But of course what happens when
two million people have

00:03:33.080 --> 00:03:35.810
read your book is it becomes
something else.

00:03:35.810 --> 00:03:39.210
It goes from being my
book to your book.

00:03:39.210 --> 00:03:41.850
And one of the things that has
happened over and over again,

00:03:41.850 --> 00:03:45.070
I've talked to thousands of
people around the world in

00:03:45.070 --> 00:03:45.960
this last year.

00:03:45.960 --> 00:03:49.230
And they all tell me their
relationship to the book,

00:03:49.230 --> 00:03:52.130
their stories about the book,
the pieces of it that

00:03:52.130 --> 00:03:54.550
intrigued them or infuriated
them or whatever

00:03:54.550 --> 00:03:56.030
the book did to them.

00:03:56.030 --> 00:03:57.920
And so they've sort
of made it theirs.

00:03:57.920 --> 00:03:59.960
CHRISTINE: Your writing, I
think, is so emotional.

00:03:59.960 --> 00:04:04.080
And it's so honest, I think, so
raw about experiences that

00:04:04.080 --> 00:04:04.695
happened to you.

00:04:04.695 --> 00:04:07.180
It's seems like you're very,
very forthcoming about things.

00:04:07.180 --> 00:04:10.680
And I think I'm curious as to
what it's like as a writer to

00:04:10.680 --> 00:04:13.870
have something that's so close
to your heart that then goes

00:04:13.870 --> 00:04:18.940
out into the world and sort of
morphs into its own beast?

00:04:18.940 --> 00:04:21.810
What is that like?

00:04:21.810 --> 00:04:22.710
CHERYL STRAYED: The couple
months right

00:04:22.710 --> 00:04:23.680
before "Wild" came out--

00:04:23.680 --> 00:04:25.590
I'm just gonna set this down.

00:04:25.590 --> 00:04:27.030
The couple months before "Wild"

00:04:27.030 --> 00:04:29.200
came out, I was terrified.

00:04:29.200 --> 00:04:31.110
I had been writing the
"Dear Sugar" column.

00:04:31.110 --> 00:04:34.380
I'd written essays that had
been read widely that were

00:04:34.380 --> 00:04:37.030
very vulnerable and raw.

00:04:37.030 --> 00:04:41.510
But I had never published a book
that was essentially my

00:04:41.510 --> 00:04:42.750
heart on the page.

00:04:42.750 --> 00:04:45.310
I mean, my first book, "Torch,"
is my heart on the

00:04:45.310 --> 00:04:47.420
page, but it's fiction.

00:04:47.420 --> 00:04:50.220
And so even though there are
all these pieces of "Torch"

00:04:50.220 --> 00:04:56.450
that are, in fact, very true,
there was this screen between

00:04:56.450 --> 00:04:57.980
me and the reader where
I could say,

00:04:57.980 --> 00:04:59.510
well, this is a fiction.

00:04:59.510 --> 00:05:01.710
"Wild," I was saying
the opposite.

00:05:01.710 --> 00:05:03.230
I was saying this is me.

00:05:03.230 --> 00:05:04.700
This is my story.

00:05:04.700 --> 00:05:06.650
If somebody doesn't like
the book-- and I

00:05:06.650 --> 00:05:07.510
mean, I've seen this.

00:05:07.510 --> 00:05:08.870
I try not to read--

00:05:08.870 --> 00:05:12.860
I try not to Google myself.

00:05:12.860 --> 00:05:18.175
Because really for a writer,
that's a dangerous prospect.

00:05:18.175 --> 00:05:20.690
And I get these Google
alerts every day.

00:05:20.690 --> 00:05:26.110
And I try to sort of skim and
not really actually read what

00:05:26.110 --> 00:05:27.090
people have written about me.

00:05:27.090 --> 00:05:29.350
And people have written all
kinds of really nice

00:05:29.350 --> 00:05:30.330
things about me.

00:05:30.330 --> 00:05:32.050
And then some people have
written really nasty

00:05:32.050 --> 00:05:33.820
things about me.

00:05:33.820 --> 00:05:37.730
And what's happening is that
character in that book is me.

00:05:37.730 --> 00:05:39.090
And so if they don't like
the book, they think

00:05:39.090 --> 00:05:39.870
they don't like me.

00:05:39.870 --> 00:05:42.040
Or if they do like the book,
they think they like me.

00:05:42.040 --> 00:05:44.780
And, a couple of nights ago
I was giving a reading.

00:05:44.780 --> 00:05:46.870
And afterwards, this woman came
up with her book and she

00:05:46.870 --> 00:05:48.190
said, I'm so glad
I came tonight.

00:05:48.190 --> 00:05:49.310
And I said think you.

00:05:49.310 --> 00:05:51.840
And she said I didn't think I
was gonna like you at all.

00:05:54.410 --> 00:05:58.270
And I was like, oh, thank you.

00:05:58.270 --> 00:05:59.760
And I didn't even want
to explore what she

00:05:59.760 --> 00:06:02.810
meant by that because--

00:06:02.810 --> 00:06:05.710
What she was saying is you in
person, I like you in person.

00:06:05.710 --> 00:06:08.220
But I think she had
some misgivings

00:06:08.220 --> 00:06:09.600
about me on the page.

00:06:09.600 --> 00:06:12.650
And so this is an incredibly
scary thing.

00:06:12.650 --> 00:06:15.190
And yet it's the
writer's work.

00:06:15.190 --> 00:06:16.160
It's the whole deal.

00:06:16.160 --> 00:06:17.960
Not just the writer,
any artist.

00:06:17.960 --> 00:06:21.400
I walked past some paintings
when we were coming in here.

00:06:21.400 --> 00:06:25.250
And that is this person taking
a great amount of risk and

00:06:25.250 --> 00:06:26.460
presenting it to you.

00:06:26.460 --> 00:06:29.340
And you get to say whether you
like it or you don't like it.

00:06:29.340 --> 00:06:34.090
And so you're either accepting
or rejecting really something

00:06:34.090 --> 00:06:37.150
that is this person's like
greatest passion.

00:06:37.150 --> 00:06:39.640
And, it's a big deal.

00:06:39.640 --> 00:06:42.020
And I had to really come to
grips with the fact that like

00:06:42.020 --> 00:06:44.450
there's never been a book
written that everyone loves.

00:06:44.450 --> 00:06:48.140
I'm OK with the fact that some
people hate the book and some

00:06:48.140 --> 00:06:49.030
people love the book.

00:06:49.030 --> 00:06:53.270
But, I've had to step
back from it.

00:06:53.270 --> 00:06:55.270
CHRISTINE: One of the craziest
things that I think must have

00:06:55.270 --> 00:06:55.740
happened to you--

00:06:55.740 --> 00:06:58.970
this is from my perspective, of
course-- but I understand

00:06:58.970 --> 00:07:01.280
that Reese Witherspoon requested
your book before it

00:07:01.280 --> 00:07:03.910
was even published and then
optioned it essentially before

00:07:03.910 --> 00:07:05.300
it was out on the presses.

00:07:05.300 --> 00:07:09.010
And so, now there's going to be
a big screen movie of your

00:07:09.010 --> 00:07:12.630
life, of an incredibly raw part
of your life that is also

00:07:12.630 --> 00:07:14.320
going to be made in Hollywood.

00:07:14.320 --> 00:07:17.880
And letting go of that control
must be something difficult to

00:07:17.880 --> 00:07:20.130
contemplate?

00:07:20.130 --> 00:07:21.520
CHERYL STRAYED: Just last
week, I read the script.

00:07:21.520 --> 00:07:22.760
So, you're right.

00:07:22.760 --> 00:07:25.930
About three months before
"Wild" came out,

00:07:25.930 --> 00:07:27.760
I got a film agent.

00:07:27.760 --> 00:07:31.200
And in just all right in one
day, the film agent said,

00:07:31.200 --> 00:07:33.390
there are three women in
Hollywood under the age of 40

00:07:33.390 --> 00:07:34.770
who can get a movie made.

00:07:34.770 --> 00:07:38.410
And they knew that the challenge
of "Wild" is the

00:07:38.410 --> 00:07:39.890
main character is a woman.

00:07:39.890 --> 00:07:43.240
And there are a bunch of men in
the book, but none of them

00:07:43.240 --> 00:07:45.380
are really main characters.

00:07:45.380 --> 00:07:47.260
And so that's already
problematic.

00:07:47.260 --> 00:07:52.900
Hollywood doesn't want to make
a movie featuring a woman.

00:07:52.900 --> 00:07:57.270
And so, right away my film agent
said, so we need to find

00:07:57.270 --> 00:07:59.320
an actress who feels
passionately about the book

00:07:59.320 --> 00:08:01.950
and will take it on
as her project.

00:08:01.950 --> 00:08:04.120
And she said, I just was
chatting with Reese

00:08:04.120 --> 00:08:07.020
Witherspoon, and she said she'd
loved to read your book

00:08:07.020 --> 00:08:07.970
over the weekend.

00:08:07.970 --> 00:08:09.660
So this was a Friday.

00:08:09.660 --> 00:08:11.590
Would you let Reese read it?

00:08:11.590 --> 00:08:13.070
And I was like sure.

00:08:13.070 --> 00:08:14.280
I mean, why not?

00:08:14.280 --> 00:08:16.400
CHRISTINE: Yeah.

00:08:16.400 --> 00:08:16.620
I guess.

00:08:16.620 --> 00:08:20.670
CHERYL STRAYED: And so, and
then I lit a candle--

00:08:20.670 --> 00:08:25.300
which I don't necessarily
believe that lighting a candle

00:08:25.300 --> 00:08:30.640
has any actual impact on the
world-- but I light a candle

00:08:30.640 --> 00:08:35.049
and every time I passed it or
looked at it I'd say, Reese.

00:08:35.049 --> 00:08:40.346
And, I can't believe I'm telling
you this actually.

00:08:40.346 --> 00:08:42.350
I've only said this
two times now.

00:08:42.350 --> 00:08:44.159
This is the second time.

00:08:44.159 --> 00:08:47.960
So, it's 'cause you guys gave
me ice cream at lunch.

00:08:47.960 --> 00:08:50.430
CHRISTINE: Really
good ice cream.

00:08:50.430 --> 00:08:56.090
CHERYL STRAYED: And so then
Monday, my cell phone rang.

00:08:56.090 --> 00:08:59.805
And it was my agent saying,
Reese loves it and she wants

00:08:59.805 --> 00:09:02.140
to option it and she wants
to talk to you.

00:09:02.140 --> 00:09:06.660
And so, Reese and I just had
this hour long conversation

00:09:06.660 --> 00:09:09.740
where she just told me
everything she understood

00:09:09.740 --> 00:09:11.910
about the book, everything
she felt about the book.

00:09:11.910 --> 00:09:15.480
And I could see right away that
she got it, that she was

00:09:15.480 --> 00:09:21.710
really deeply connected to
the story I was telling.

00:09:21.710 --> 00:09:26.360
And then she was sharing with me
all parts of herself as an

00:09:26.360 --> 00:09:29.320
artist, too, as an actress,
what she could

00:09:29.320 --> 00:09:30.240
bring to the story.

00:09:30.240 --> 00:09:34.380
Because that's the deal is it is
gonna be strange when I see

00:09:34.380 --> 00:09:37.260
the movie and there's
Reese and she's me.

00:09:37.260 --> 00:09:40.150
But it's also I've had
to let that go.

00:09:40.150 --> 00:09:41.280
Because I wrote the book.

00:09:41.280 --> 00:09:43.555
Nobody can change the book.

00:09:43.555 --> 00:09:45.150
That was my creation.

00:09:45.150 --> 00:09:47.090
The film isn't my creation.

00:09:47.090 --> 00:09:51.230
And so Reese is gonna have to
make it hers in order for it

00:09:51.230 --> 00:09:52.430
to succeed.

00:09:52.430 --> 00:09:56.050
I really think that anything
that is made with artistic

00:09:56.050 --> 00:09:59.860
intentions, it has to come
from a core place.

00:09:59.860 --> 00:10:02.050
It has to come from an
authentic place.

00:10:02.050 --> 00:10:08.700
And so she can't be trying to
sort of mimic me in the course

00:10:08.700 --> 00:10:10.130
of making the film.

00:10:10.130 --> 00:10:12.040
So I have just great
confidence in her.

00:10:12.040 --> 00:10:14.460
I think she's really smart
and really kind of--

00:10:14.460 --> 00:10:18.820
and I've met her and had long
conversations with her.

00:10:18.820 --> 00:10:19.880
I couldn't be more thrilled.

00:10:19.880 --> 00:10:20.680
And she hired--

00:10:20.680 --> 00:10:25.480
I didn't want anything to do
with the script, so she hired

00:10:25.480 --> 00:10:27.220
Nick Hornby, the writer
Nick Hornby--

00:10:27.220 --> 00:10:27.550
CHRISTINE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:10:27.550 --> 00:10:28.720
CHERYL STRAYED: --to
write the script.

00:10:28.720 --> 00:10:31.020
And so then I went to England
in January for the "Wild"

00:10:31.020 --> 00:10:33.900
launch there, and I hung out
with Nick for several days.

00:10:33.900 --> 00:10:36.490
And it was so strange 'cause
I met him and he's been

00:10:36.490 --> 00:10:38.310
obsessively thinking
about me for like

00:10:38.310 --> 00:10:40.112
the last three months.

00:10:40.112 --> 00:10:41.450
He's like, Cheryl--

00:10:41.450 --> 00:10:42.450
and it was just this--

00:10:42.450 --> 00:10:43.936
CHRISTINE: So have I,
just by the way.

00:10:43.936 --> 00:10:45.688
CHERYL STRAYED: Have you?

00:10:45.688 --> 00:10:49.515
And we just had this really
intense experience together.

00:10:49.515 --> 00:10:51.060
And last week I read
the script.

00:10:51.060 --> 00:10:53.850
I was afraid to ask him for it
because I was like, oh, what

00:10:53.850 --> 00:10:54.690
if I don't like it?

00:10:54.690 --> 00:10:56.310
He sent it to me, and
it's really good.

00:10:56.310 --> 00:10:56.790
It's great.

00:10:56.790 --> 00:10:57.340
CHRISTINE: That's wonderful.

00:10:57.340 --> 00:10:58.880
CHERYL STRAYED: So, the
hope is that it'll

00:10:58.880 --> 00:11:00.190
be shot this summer.

00:11:00.190 --> 00:11:03.260
There are all these logistics
that need to be worked out.

00:11:03.260 --> 00:11:03.900
And who knows.

00:11:03.900 --> 00:11:04.770
It's Hollywood.

00:11:04.770 --> 00:11:05.690
You never know.

00:11:05.690 --> 00:11:08.900
But, there are good
things happening.

00:11:08.900 --> 00:11:10.990
CHRISTINE: So when you play the
game of who would play you

00:11:10.990 --> 00:11:15.450
in a movie, did you ever think
it would be Reese Witherspoon?

00:11:15.450 --> 00:11:16.540
CHERYL STRAYED: Yeah.

00:11:16.540 --> 00:11:18.380
I never did.

00:11:18.380 --> 00:11:21.840
I never could think of an
answer to that question.

00:11:21.840 --> 00:11:22.235
CHRISTINE: Now you know.

00:11:22.235 --> 00:11:22.700
You don't even have to--

00:11:22.700 --> 00:11:23.520
CHERYL STRAYED: Now I know.

00:11:23.520 --> 00:11:23.940
It's really--

00:11:23.940 --> 00:11:24.590
CHRISTINE: --play the
game anymore.

00:11:24.590 --> 00:11:25.720
CHERYL STRAYED: Isn't
that interesting?

00:11:25.720 --> 00:11:26.070
Yeah.

00:11:26.070 --> 00:11:27.360
So it'll be Reese.

00:11:27.360 --> 00:11:29.850
CHRISTINE: Well, let's talk
about the book a bit.

00:11:29.850 --> 00:11:33.270
So, the book is about
your memoir of

00:11:33.270 --> 00:11:34.465
your hike up the PCT.

00:11:34.465 --> 00:11:37.370
It's 1,000 miles, three
months alone.

00:11:37.370 --> 00:11:38.770
You were 26 at the
time, right?

00:11:38.770 --> 00:11:39.310
CHERYL STRAYED: Um-um.

00:11:39.310 --> 00:11:43.700
CHRISTINE: And, to me that's
just a startling undertaking.

00:11:43.700 --> 00:11:46.160
And I hear that lots of women
are now being inspired to do

00:11:46.160 --> 00:11:47.280
this by themselves.

00:11:47.280 --> 00:11:50.990
But, one of the themes of the
book, one of the things that

00:11:50.990 --> 00:11:53.440
you're open and honest about,
is that you were completely

00:11:53.440 --> 00:11:54.860
ill prepared for it.

00:11:54.860 --> 00:11:58.200
So, I guess one of the things
that I think about is if you

00:11:58.200 --> 00:11:59.850
were to do it again, would you
have done it differently?

00:11:59.850 --> 00:12:01.590
Would you have planned
it differently?

00:12:01.590 --> 00:12:03.610
Would you have thought
it through?

00:12:03.610 --> 00:12:05.090
Would you have gone
with a group?

00:12:05.090 --> 00:12:06.630
Are there things about the hike
that you would have done

00:12:06.630 --> 00:12:07.270
differently?

00:12:07.270 --> 00:12:08.600
CHERYL STRAYED: Well, I
certainly would not have gone

00:12:08.600 --> 00:12:09.840
with anyone.

00:12:09.840 --> 00:12:12.860
I think that being alone was a
really important piece of it.

00:12:12.860 --> 00:12:14.530
And I still love to
travel alone.

00:12:14.530 --> 00:12:16.150
I love to do things alone.

00:12:16.150 --> 00:12:19.180
You just exist in the world in
a different way when you are

00:12:19.180 --> 00:12:21.280
by yourself, whether you're
a man or a woman.

00:12:21.280 --> 00:12:26.500
And I do think that there's
something about solitude,

00:12:26.500 --> 00:12:29.740
especially in wild places,
that you go

00:12:29.740 --> 00:12:32.010
into a deeper solitude.

00:12:32.010 --> 00:12:35.280
And also that when you're
by yourself, you

00:12:35.280 --> 00:12:37.510
have to rely on yourself.

00:12:37.510 --> 00:12:42.042
You have to literally carry
your own weight.

00:12:42.042 --> 00:12:44.150
You are the beast of
your own burden.

00:12:44.150 --> 00:12:47.700
And I think that was an
incredibly powerful thing for

00:12:47.700 --> 00:12:48.920
me at that moment in my life.

00:12:48.920 --> 00:12:51.890
I think it would be a powerful
thing for me at any moment in

00:12:51.890 --> 00:12:54.830
my life, but I think
particularly then.

00:12:54.830 --> 00:12:58.070
And as far as preparing, I
mean one of things that's

00:12:58.070 --> 00:12:58.520
interesting--

00:12:58.520 --> 00:13:00.100
I've been really thinking
about this 'cause this

00:13:00.100 --> 00:13:03.020
question comes up a lot--

00:13:03.020 --> 00:13:06.500
I did so much preparation
before my hike.

00:13:06.500 --> 00:13:08.040
I had to pack those boxes.

00:13:08.040 --> 00:13:09.110
I had to dehydrate food.

00:13:09.110 --> 00:13:13.270
I had to figure out these little
Podunk stops along the

00:13:13.270 --> 00:13:16.240
way and calculate how long it
would take me to get them.

00:13:16.240 --> 00:13:17.450
CHRISTINE: And there
was no Google then.

00:13:17.450 --> 00:13:18.290
CHERYL STRAYED: And there
was no-- that's

00:13:18.290 --> 00:13:18.960
what I was gonna say--

00:13:18.960 --> 00:13:19.980
and there was no Google.

00:13:19.980 --> 00:13:23.200
And, so I think a lot of times
people say, oh, you were so

00:13:23.200 --> 00:13:24.020
ill prepared.

00:13:24.020 --> 00:13:26.750
They're forgetting the
world of 1995.

00:13:26.750 --> 00:13:31.420
I was on the PCT when somebody
for the first time explained

00:13:31.420 --> 00:13:33.330
to me what email was.

00:13:33.330 --> 00:13:37.400
And I could not understand
what she was saying.

00:13:37.400 --> 00:13:39.260
And I remember saying, so you're
sitting there at your

00:13:39.260 --> 00:13:42.750
computer and then a letter
appears on the screen?

00:13:42.750 --> 00:13:45.130
And she was like, yeah, it's
kind of like that.

00:13:45.130 --> 00:13:47.120
And I was like, that seems
totally weird.

00:13:47.120 --> 00:13:49.790
The other thing is I was also
on the PCT the first time I

00:13:49.790 --> 00:13:50.990
heard of a cell phone.

00:13:50.990 --> 00:13:53.830
So those of you who have read
the book, the guy Albert who

00:13:53.830 --> 00:13:56.640
was like this Eagle Scout who
helps me lighten my load and

00:13:56.640 --> 00:14:00.110
like finds the condoms and all
that, this guy, he was like

00:14:00.110 --> 00:14:00.920
Mr. Lightweight.

00:14:00.920 --> 00:14:05.810
But he did have this huge brick
of plastic with numbers

00:14:05.810 --> 00:14:06.940
on the front.

00:14:06.940 --> 00:14:08.800
And I said, what is this?

00:14:08.800 --> 00:14:11.570
And he said it's a stupid
thing that I have been

00:14:11.570 --> 00:14:13.860
carrying now for 500
miles now, and I'm

00:14:13.860 --> 00:14:15.670
gonna dump it here.

00:14:15.670 --> 00:14:17.630
It's a thing called
a cell phone.

00:14:17.630 --> 00:14:20.450
And this company had found out--
that was like trying to

00:14:20.450 --> 00:14:23.040
make these early cell phones--
had found out he was taking

00:14:23.040 --> 00:14:26.070
the PCT and wanted him
to carry it to see--

00:14:26.070 --> 00:14:27.440
and he'd have to turn
it on once a day to

00:14:27.440 --> 00:14:28.700
see if he got reception.

00:14:28.700 --> 00:14:30.910
And he'd never got reception.

00:14:30.910 --> 00:14:34.110
And he's like, I'm not
carrying this.

00:14:34.110 --> 00:14:38.100
And I remember us sitting around
this campfire and the

00:14:38.100 --> 00:14:43.270
absolute consensus without any
question was this is a product

00:14:43.270 --> 00:14:48.340
that is never gonna fly because
who would want to walk

00:14:48.340 --> 00:14:50.330
around with a phone in their
pocket all the time?

00:14:50.330 --> 00:14:51.300
I mean, who would want--

00:14:51.300 --> 00:14:53.650
I mean, right?

00:14:53.650 --> 00:14:55.610
Which is so funny now,
'cause I'm like--

00:14:55.610 --> 00:14:57.305
CHRISTINE: That's like 15 years
ago we're talking about

00:14:57.305 --> 00:14:57.580
at this point.

00:14:57.580 --> 00:14:57.900
CHERYL STRAYED: I know.

00:14:57.900 --> 00:14:58.850
CHRISTINE: Like that's
amazing.

00:14:58.850 --> 00:14:59.060
CHERYL STRAYED: I know.

00:14:59.060 --> 00:15:00.560
That's what's so
crazy about it.

00:15:00.560 --> 00:15:01.920
So the world changed
really quickly.

00:15:01.920 --> 00:15:03.400
We could Google--

00:15:03.400 --> 00:15:07.390
I mean, I swear I think I use
Google like 500 times a day.

00:15:07.390 --> 00:15:07.670
CHRISTINE: We all do.

00:15:07.670 --> 00:15:09.570
CHERYL STRAYED: We all do.

00:15:09.570 --> 00:15:12.150
We could have hundreds, maybe
thousands of trail

00:15:12.150 --> 00:15:13.650
journals, in a snap.

00:15:13.650 --> 00:15:17.040
People now, they blog
from the PCT.

00:15:17.040 --> 00:15:20.350
I have tweeted on my iPhone
from the PCT.

00:15:20.350 --> 00:15:21.570
Different world then.

00:15:21.570 --> 00:15:24.000
Like my communication with the
world is if you wanted to get

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:26.550
in touch with me, you'd write
a letter to a post office

00:15:26.550 --> 00:15:29.300
where you thought I might be
in a couple weeks and write

00:15:29.300 --> 00:15:31.530
general delivery, Cheryl
Strayed and the

00:15:31.530 --> 00:15:33.410
town and the zip code.

00:15:33.410 --> 00:15:35.000
CHRISTINE: Which is interesting
because that's the

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:37.003
way that we would have
communicated for hundreds of

00:15:37.003 --> 00:15:37.050
years before--

00:15:37.050 --> 00:15:37.400
CHERYL STRAYED: Hundreds
of year.

00:15:37.400 --> 00:15:37.950
CHRISTINE: -that.

00:15:37.950 --> 00:15:39.680
And in a mere 15, 16 years--

00:15:39.680 --> 00:15:40.040
CHERYL STRAYED: Yeah.

00:15:40.040 --> 00:15:41.525
CHRISTINE: --at this point,
it's utterly changed.

00:15:41.525 --> 00:15:43.840
CHERYL STRAYED: It's
totally different.

00:15:43.840 --> 00:15:45.860
And I remember, I bought
that guidebook at

00:15:45.860 --> 00:15:47.450
REI, the PCT guidebook.

00:15:47.450 --> 00:15:49.780
And I went to the Minneapolis
Public Library because I

00:15:49.780 --> 00:15:51.520
wanted to read more
about the PCT.

00:15:51.520 --> 00:15:54.122
And they didn't have any
other books about it.

00:15:54.122 --> 00:15:54.950
And that was it.

00:15:54.950 --> 00:15:56.580
That was the end
of my research.

00:15:56.580 --> 00:16:00.940
The piece of it that you're
right about that I didn't

00:16:00.940 --> 00:16:02.800
prepare physically.

00:16:02.800 --> 00:16:06.900
I mean, I don't know,, drinking
a lot, doing heroin,

00:16:06.900 --> 00:16:07.720
sleeping with a lot of guys.

00:16:07.720 --> 00:16:09.000
It's not really a great
preparation for--

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:10.250
CHRISTINE: Not the
best training.

00:16:12.650 --> 00:16:13.710
CHERYL STRAYED: So I did that.

00:16:13.710 --> 00:16:14.960
So that was a mistake.

00:16:17.240 --> 00:16:19.960
I wouldn't recommend
those things.

00:16:19.960 --> 00:16:23.690
And I also just didn't know
how hard it would be.

00:16:23.690 --> 00:16:26.660
I had this idea of being
in the wild.

00:16:26.660 --> 00:16:28.220
And I had been a day hiker.

00:16:28.220 --> 00:16:30.460
And I thought, well, it's
kind of like that.

00:16:30.460 --> 00:16:31.900
But it's not like that.

00:16:31.900 --> 00:16:34.960
It was much harder and much
more remote than I

00:16:34.960 --> 00:16:36.110
thought it would be.

00:16:36.110 --> 00:16:38.460
But having said that, I don't
think I would do anything

00:16:38.460 --> 00:16:38.820
differently.

00:16:38.820 --> 00:16:41.300
I would get better
boots that fit.

00:16:41.300 --> 00:16:43.550
And I would take fewer things.

00:16:43.550 --> 00:16:47.070
But I'm glad in retrospect
that I had exactly the

00:16:47.070 --> 00:16:50.580
experience I did because I'd
learned the hard way, and all

00:16:50.580 --> 00:16:52.730
the best things I've learned
the hard way.

00:16:52.730 --> 00:16:55.570
Because the thing about that
is you never forget then.

00:16:55.570 --> 00:17:01.470
And, I think I needed to have
a sort of reckoning.

00:17:01.470 --> 00:17:08.420
And, I suffered the consequences
of all of my

00:17:08.420 --> 00:17:10.329
decisions on the trail.

00:17:10.329 --> 00:17:11.284
And that was an incredibly--

00:17:11.284 --> 00:17:11.720
CHRISTINE: In a very, very--

00:17:11.720 --> 00:17:13.510
CHERYL STRAYED: --empowering
experience, in a really

00:17:13.510 --> 00:17:14.250
physical way.

00:17:14.250 --> 00:17:15.369
CHRISTINE: Right.

00:17:15.369 --> 00:17:18.329
I guess I've heard you say in
other forums that putting

00:17:18.329 --> 00:17:20.530
yourself through the physical
pain sort of helped you cope

00:17:20.530 --> 00:17:21.990
with the emotional pain.

00:17:21.990 --> 00:17:24.920
And, I don't know what the
question is here, but that's

00:17:24.920 --> 00:17:26.250
very, I think, powerful.

00:17:26.250 --> 00:17:28.329
And to understand that, I mean,
I think that's something

00:17:28.329 --> 00:17:31.400
I do in my life is that you
focus on something else so

00:17:31.400 --> 00:17:33.510
that the other things can
process behind you.

00:17:33.510 --> 00:17:33.880
CHERYL STRAYED: Yeah.

00:17:33.880 --> 00:17:34.870
CHRISTINE: Which is cool.

00:17:34.870 --> 00:17:37.484
CHERYL STRAYED: I think
that that's true.

00:17:37.484 --> 00:17:40.680
I think, too, one of the
things I maybe didn't

00:17:40.680 --> 00:17:44.180
consciously realize at the time
is that I was creating my

00:17:44.180 --> 00:17:45.250
own rite of passage.

00:17:45.250 --> 00:17:48.090
We don't really have this
in our culture.

00:17:48.090 --> 00:17:48.850
And we all know--

00:17:48.850 --> 00:17:51.600
I mean, some of you in the
room are in your 20s, but

00:17:51.600 --> 00:17:55.400
those of you who have gone
beyond those years know that

00:17:55.400 --> 00:17:58.450
even if things had been going
really well for me, even if

00:17:58.450 --> 00:18:02.250
I'd had like a great father and
a mom who didn't die at 45

00:18:02.250 --> 00:18:05.010
of cancer, all of these
different things that sort of

00:18:05.010 --> 00:18:08.990
combined to get me at that place
in my life of despair

00:18:08.990 --> 00:18:11.740
that I was at, I would
still have had to

00:18:11.740 --> 00:18:13.400
figure out who I was.

00:18:13.400 --> 00:18:18.320
And I would still would have had
to figure out what path I

00:18:18.320 --> 00:18:20.160
was gonna take and also
how to survive and

00:18:20.160 --> 00:18:21.390
thrive on that path.

00:18:21.390 --> 00:18:27.510
Because I was choosing a path
of the writer, which can be

00:18:27.510 --> 00:18:29.930
seen sort of as an illegitimate
path for quite a

00:18:29.930 --> 00:18:30.860
number of years.

00:18:30.860 --> 00:18:33.960
I was a waitress, and I'd say,
well, I'm a waitress but I'm

00:18:33.960 --> 00:18:34.710
really a writer.

00:18:34.710 --> 00:18:38.280
And people, they scoff at that
or they roll their eyes or

00:18:38.280 --> 00:18:40.010
they're when are you gonna get
a real job, all of that stuff

00:18:40.010 --> 00:18:44.120
you have to endure when you have
taken that other path.

00:18:44.120 --> 00:18:50.060
And so I needed to go through
some sort of rite that would

00:18:50.060 --> 00:18:52.990
take me to that next place
of growing up.

00:18:52.990 --> 00:18:54.090
And I needed to heal.

00:18:54.090 --> 00:18:56.850
I needed to heal all of that
stuff that you mentioned.

00:18:56.850 --> 00:19:00.320
And so I think I didn't
know quite what I was.

00:19:00.320 --> 00:19:01.960
Like I said, I didn't know
what I was getting into

00:19:01.960 --> 00:19:02.560
physically.

00:19:02.560 --> 00:19:05.950
But once I was out there, I
realized it was very physical

00:19:05.950 --> 00:19:07.870
and it was exactly
what I needed.

00:19:07.870 --> 00:19:12.310
I was suffering on the inside,
and suddenly I forgot about

00:19:12.310 --> 00:19:16.150
those things because I was
suffering so much physically.

00:19:16.150 --> 00:19:17.430
CHRISTINE: One of the things
I think that's really

00:19:17.430 --> 00:19:19.720
interesting about this book
that I've realized only in

00:19:19.720 --> 00:19:22.205
retrospect and when you talk
about the rite of passage it

00:19:22.205 --> 00:19:26.370
brings it up to me is that I
think your memoir is very much

00:19:26.370 --> 00:19:29.210
sort of a female archetype
story, like sort of a feminine

00:19:29.210 --> 00:19:30.560
superhero in some ways.

00:19:30.560 --> 00:19:33.390
I mean, you did this
rite of passage.

00:19:33.390 --> 00:19:35.150
You were doing it on your own.

00:19:35.150 --> 00:19:38.470
And you're sort of creating your
own archetype or tapping

00:19:38.470 --> 00:19:44.380
into an architect that isn't
necessarily out there for a

00:19:44.380 --> 00:19:46.180
female archetype.

00:19:46.180 --> 00:19:48.390
It's something that you see in
a lot of male role models.

00:19:48.390 --> 00:19:51.300
And that's more what you touch
on in popular culture.

00:19:51.300 --> 00:19:54.450
But, you were doing this as a
woman, and there wasn't a lot

00:19:54.450 --> 00:19:55.280
out there that time.

00:19:55.280 --> 00:19:59.090
And so I think to me it's
interesting that you--

00:19:59.090 --> 00:20:02.490
I guess my question to you is
did you consciously write with

00:20:02.490 --> 00:20:04.470
that archetype in mind?

00:20:04.470 --> 00:20:06.400
Because to me this is also
just your story.

00:20:06.400 --> 00:20:08.140
And this is just something
that you did.

00:20:08.140 --> 00:20:11.350
But at the same time you are
tapping into those themes.

00:20:11.350 --> 00:20:13.820
CHERYL STRAYED: Yeah.

00:20:13.820 --> 00:20:15.830
I teach memoir writing
sometimes.

00:20:15.830 --> 00:20:20.620
A lot of people, when they first
began to write creative

00:20:20.620 --> 00:20:24.040
nonfiction or memoir, stories
from their lives, they'll come

00:20:24.040 --> 00:20:29.440
to me and say, well, you know my
son died or I spent a year

00:20:29.440 --> 00:20:33.050
in France or I climbed Mount
Kilimanjaro after surviving

00:20:33.050 --> 00:20:37.140
breast cancer, whatever
story they have.

00:20:37.140 --> 00:20:40.990
And they're impulse is to write
that story because they

00:20:40.990 --> 00:20:44.010
had the experience and the
experience was dramatic or

00:20:44.010 --> 00:20:47.710
traumatic or adventuresome or
whatever, any of those things.

00:20:47.710 --> 00:20:51.140
And I always say, the experience
isn't enough.

00:20:51.140 --> 00:20:54.560
We've all had traumas and
dramas and adventures.

00:20:54.560 --> 00:21:00.060
And there's a difference between
having a great dinner

00:21:00.060 --> 00:21:03.500
party conversation about an
experience you had and writing

00:21:03.500 --> 00:21:05.860
a great book or writing
a great essay.

00:21:05.860 --> 00:21:09.530
And the difference is the
consciousness you bring to

00:21:09.530 --> 00:21:10.250
bear on it.

00:21:10.250 --> 00:21:13.430
Well, first of all it's
the writing craft.

00:21:13.430 --> 00:21:17.230
You have to actually know how to
write sentences that people

00:21:17.230 --> 00:21:18.510
want to read.

00:21:18.510 --> 00:21:18.950
But then--

00:21:18.950 --> 00:21:20.426
CHRISTINE: Which you do
really, really well.

00:21:20.426 --> 00:21:21.360
CHERYL STRAYED: Oh, thank you.

00:21:21.360 --> 00:21:24.490
But then, what consciousness
are you bringing to bear?

00:21:24.490 --> 00:21:26.110
What awareness?

00:21:26.110 --> 00:21:27.660
What does this thing mean?

